climbs.name: Rare Earth
climbs.fa: Traeanne Reynolds, Gordon Briody, Brian Steele (1998)

content.description: The namesake route of this crag, and one of the better 10a friction climbs in the icicle. the first 2/3rds is sustained edging and friction, with it letting up slightly as the angle lowers towards the top.
content.location: right side of the wall, and the only fully bolted route. Look for the white streak.

content.description: as the name implies, this is an old school route where the 5.8 crux is protected by a rusty piton.
content.location: on the lower tier of Rare earth. a scramble leads down the right side to the route, or hike up from above domestic dome.

content.description: A variation of Rare Earth climbing to the right of the bolt line on a somewhat dirty flake, that reconnects to Rare earth near the chains.
content.protection: gear to 2". 1 bolt. shares anchor chains with Rare Earth.

content.description:
A pleasant hand/finger crack on the far left side of the wall. Climb a slightly flaring fingers and hand crack until the crack runs out. there is 1 bolt protecting the easy slab moves at the top.

can easily be toproped.
content.protection: cams from #.5-#2 plus a draw for the bolt. 2 bolt anchor (no chains)
content.location: left side of the wall. if traversing from Givler's/Wart wall area, this will be the first route you reach.
